05362nam a22006735i 9780520938205DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20052005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209382057 a10.1525/97805209382052doi  a(DE-B1597)648627  a(OCoLC)1261024823  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBX 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a255/.9/009722221 aLester, Rebecca J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJesus in Our Wombs :bEmbodying Modernity in a Mexican Convent /cRebecca J. Lester; ed. by Rebecca J. Lester. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (358 p.) :b6 line illustrations, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEthnographic Studies in Subjectivity00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Contexts -- t1. Female Bodies and the Touch of God -- t2. The Siervas -- t3. Religious Formation -- tPart Two. Becoming Women in Christ -- t4. Brokenness: Restless in My Own Skin -- t5. Belonging: Sisters in Arms -- t6. Containment: Producing the Interior -- t7. Regimentation: Making the Mindful Body -- t8. Self-Critique: Diagnosing the Soul -- t9. Surrender: Turning It Over to God -- t10. Re/Collection: The Temporal Contours of the Self -- t11. Changing the Subject: Transformations -- tPart Three. Articulations -- t12. Mexican Modernities -- t13. Bodies and Selves: Theorizing Embodiment -- tAppendix: Glossary of Catholic Terms and Selected Central Prayers -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Jesus in Our Wombs, Rebecca J. Lester takes us behind the walls of a Roman Catholic convent in central Mexico to explore the lives, training, and experiences of a group of postulants—young women in the first stage of religious training as nuns. Lester, who conducted eighteen months of fieldwork in the convent, provides a rich ethnography of these young women's journeys as they wrestle with doubts, fears, ambitions, and setbacks in their struggle to follow what they believe to be the will of God. Gracefully written, finely textured, and theoretically rigorous, this book considers how these aspiring nuns learn to experience God by cultivating an altered experience of their own female bodies, a transformation they view as a political stance against modernity. Lester explains that the Postulants work toward what they see as an "authentic" femininity—one that has been eclipsed by the values of modern society. The outcome of this process has political as well as personal consequences. The Sisters learn to understand their very intimate experiences of "the Call"—and their choices in answering it—as politically relevant declarations of self. Readers become intimately acquainted with the personalities, family backgrounds, friendships, and aspirations of the Postulants as Lester relates the practices and experiences of their daily lives. Combining compassionate, engaged ethnography with an incisive and provocative theoretical analysis of embodied selves, Jesus in Our Wombs delivers a profound analysis of what Lester calls the convent's "technology of embodiment" on multiple levels—from the phenomenological to the political.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFemmesxConditions socialesxAspect psychologiquexMexique. 0aMonastic and religious life of womenxPsychologyxMexico. 0aMonastic and religious life of womenzMexicoxPsychology. 0aPostulancyxPsychology. 0aPostulat (Religion)xPsychologie. 0aVie religieuse et monastique fémininexPsychologiexMexique. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxPsychological aspectsxMexico. 0aWomenzMexicoxSoci